2 Specifying production function

Cobb-Douglas production function

The Cobb-Douglas production function was specified using the formula below:

\[ \ln y_i = \alpha_0 + \sum_{j=1}^4 \ln \alpha_j X_{ji} + \sum_{m=1}^3 \delta_m D_{mi} \]

where: \(Y_i\) represents the total amount of rice produced by the farm \(i\); \(X_{ji}\) is the set of \(j\)th input of the \(i\)th farm; and \(D_{mi}\) refers to a vector of control variables of exogenous environmental factor \(m\).

# specifying the Cobb-Douglas production funtion
cd_prod <- lm(log(prod) ~ log(seed.q) + log(fert.q) + log(fl.labor.hr)
              + log(hl.labor.hr) + pestq.dum + soil_qual + topog,
              data = data_scale)

# summary results

Translog production function

The Translog production function was specified using the formula below:

\[ \ln y_i = \alpha_0 + \sum_{j=1}^4 \ln \alpha_j X_{ji} + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{j=1}^4 \sum_{k=1}^4 \alpha_{jk} \ln X_{ji} \ln X_{ki} + \sum_{m=1}^3 \delta_m D_{mi} \]

# specifying the Translog production function
translog_prod <- lm(log(prod) ~ log(seed.q) + log(fert.q) + log(fl.labor.hr)
   + log(hl.labor.hr) + I(0.5 * log(seed.q)^2) + I(0.5 * log(fert.q)^2)
   + I(0.5 * log(fl.labor.hr)^2) + I(0.5 * log(hl.labor.hr)^2) 
   + I(log(seed.q) * log(fert.q)) + I(log(seed.q) * log(fl.labor.hr)) 
   + I(log(seed.q) * log(hl.labor.hr)) + I(log(fert.q) * log(fl.labor.hr)) 
   + I(log(fert.q) * log(hl.labor.hr)) + I(log(fl.labor.hr) * log(hl.labor.hr)), 
   data = data_scale)

performance::check_model(translog_prod)

As expected, a Translog model shows high collinearity since the added parameter is a product among input used in production. However, other diagnostic tests seems fine.


3 Efficiency analysis using SFA

Cobb-Douglas SF production function

The Cobb-Douglas stochastic frontier production function was specified using the formula below:

\[ \ln y_i = \alpha_0 + \sum_{j=1}^4 \ln \alpha_j X_{ji} + \sum_{m=1}^3 \delta_m D_{mi} + V_i - U_i \]

wherein the variance is parameterized as follows:

\[ \sigma^2 = \sigma_v^2 + \sigma_u^2 ; \gamma = \sigma_u^2 / \sigma^2 (0 \le \gamma \le 1) \] here \(\sigma^2\) is assumed to be an aggregation of random events and technical efficiency. The parameter \(\gamma\) explains the impact to technical efficiency on rice production, ranging from 0 to 1. A \(\gamma\) near 0 indicates that variation of the real output from frontier output primarily derives from stochastic effects, whereas closer to 1 implies most of the random variations are caused by the effects of inefficiency.

# specifying the Cobb-Douglas stochastic frontier production function
cd_sfa <- sfa(log(prod) ~ log(seed.q) + log(fert.q) + log(fl.labor.hr)
              + log(hl.labor.hr) + pestq.dum
              + soil_qual + topog, data = data_scale)

# summary results

Translog SF production function

The Translog production function was specified using the formula below:

\[ \ln y_i = \alpha_0 + \sum_{j=1}^4 \ln \alpha_j X_{ji} + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{j=1}^4 \sum_{k=1}^4 \alpha_{jk} \ln X_{ji} \ln X_{ki} + \sum_{m=1}^3 \delta_m D_{mi} + V_i - U_i \]

wherein the variance is parameterized as follows:

\[ \sigma^2 = \sigma_v^2 + \sigma_u^2 ; \gamma = \sigma_u^2 / \sigma^2 (0 \le \gamma \le 1) \]

# specifying the Cobb-Douglas stochastic frontier production function
translog_sfa <- sfa(log(prod) ~ log(seed.q) + log(fert.q) + log(fl.labor.hr)
   + log(hl.labor.hr) + I(0.5 * log(seed.q)^2) + I(0.5 * log(fert.q)^2)
   + I(0.5 * log(fl.labor.hr)^2) + I(0.5 * log(hl.labor.hr)^2) 
   + I(log(seed.q) * log(fert.q)) + I(log(seed.q) * log(fl.labor.hr)) 
   + I(log(seed.q) * log(hl.labor.hr)) + I(log(fert.q) * log(fl.labor.hr)) 
   + I(log(fert.q) * log(hl.labor.hr)) + I(log(fl.labor.hr) * log(hl.labor.hr))
   + pestq.dum + soil_qual + topog, 
   data = data_scale)

4 Efficiency distribution across area interval

The exploratory analysis shows large variation of input and output usage across the distribution of the production area. Here, the efficiency distribution was computed across production area interval.

Efficiency distribution from CD model

# Extracting efficiency score and binding to data set
data_CDeff <- cbind(data_scale, as.data.frame(efficiencies(cd_sfa)))

# Calculating efficiency distribution across area interval
data_CDeff %>%
   mutate(area = cut(area, 3)) %>% 
   group_by(area) %>% 
   summarise(mean_TE = mean(efficiency, na.rm = T) * 100 ,
             min_TE = min(efficiency) * 100,
             max_TE  = max(efficiency) * 100,
             # calculating upper-lower bounds with 95% CI (2.26 critical value)
             lower_bound = (mean(efficiency) - 2.66 * sum(abs(diff(efficiency)))
                            / length(efficiency)) * 100,
             upper_bound = (mean(efficiency) + 2.66 * sum(abs(diff(efficiency)))
                            / length(efficiency)) * 100,
             range = (upper_bound - lower_bound)
             ) %>%

5 Test of assumptions using likelihood ratio test

The LR test is performed using the lmtest package. The test compare the fit of one model to the fit of the other. Here, the LR test was used to test the null hypotheses of the study on model choice and hypotheses.

\[ LR = 2(loglik(model2) - loglik(model1)) \]

5.1 Test on the functional form

OLS vs Cobb Douglas model

# OLS vs Cobb-Douglas
lrtest(cd_sfa) %>% 
   kable(digits = 2) %>% 
   kable_classic(full_width = F)
#Df LogLik Df Chisq Pr(>Chisq)
9 -21.39 NA NA NA
10 -19.85 1 3.07 0.04

Decision: Reject Null: OLS model; Accept alternative: Cobb-Douglas model at alpha 0.05.

OLS vs Translog

# OLS vs Translog
lrtest(translog_sfa) %>% 
   kable(digits = 2) %>% 
   kable_classic(full_width = F)
#Df LogLik Df Chisq Pr(>Chisq)
19 -15.07 NA NA NA
20 -14.10 1 1.93 0.08

Decision: Accept Null: OLS model at alpha 0.05; Accept alternative: Translog at alpha 0.10.

Cobb-Douglas vs Translog

# Cobb-Douglas vs Translog
lrtest(cd_sfa, translog_sfa) %>% 
   kable(digits = 2) %>% 
   kable_classic(full_width = F)
#Df LogLik Df Chisq Pr(>Chisq)
10 -19.85 NA NA NA
20 -14.10 10 11.5 0.32

Decision: Accept Null: Cobb-Douglas Model.

Translog Model: Half-normal vs Truncated

# estimating truncated translog SFA
translog_sfa_trunc <- sfa(log(prod) ~ log(seed.q) + log(fert.q) + log(fl.labor.hr)
   + log(hl.labor.hr) + I(0.5 * log(seed.q)^2) + I(0.5 * log(fert.q)^2)
   + I(0.5 * log(fl.labor.hr)^2) + I(0.5 * log(hl.labor.hr)^2) 
   + I(log(seed.q) * log(fert.q)) + I(log(seed.q) * log(fl.labor.hr)) 
   + I(log(seed.q) * log(hl.labor.hr)) + I(log(fert.q) * log(fl.labor.hr)) 
   + I(log(fert.q) * log(hl.labor.hr)) + I(log(fl.labor.hr) * log(hl.labor.hr)), 
   data = data_scale, truncNorm = TRUE)

# Half-normal vs Truncated
lrtest(translog_sfa, translog_sfa_trunc) %>% 
   kable(digits = 2) %>% 
   kable_classic(full_width = F)

Inputs return to scale tends to be lower for larger farm size. Seeds and fertilizer shows larger elasticity than labor inputs, implies production output are sensitive to changes in seed and fertilizer usage.

Note: Pesticide and machine input were used as control variables as they are coded as dummy variables. A significant missing values were observed on pesticides and machine input.

    + age + educ_primary + educ_secondary + hh.mem + off_farm
    + input_market + sell_market + yrs.farming
    + M54_scale, data = data_scale)

Efficiency distribution across collective activities

data_eff %>% 
   mutate(eff_int = cut(efficiency, 5, include.lowest = T)) %>% 
   group_by(ca, value, eff_int) %>% 
   summarise(frequency = n()) %>% 
   ungroup() %>% 
   mutate(eff_int = recode(eff_int,
                           '[0.526,0.613]' = "< 60",
                           '(0.613,0.699]' = "61 - 70",
                           '(0.699,0.785]' = "71 - 78",
                           '(0.785,0.872]' = "79 - 88",
                           '(0.872,0.958]' = "> 89")) %>% 
   ggplot(aes(x = eff_int, y = frequency, fill = value)) +
   geom_col(position = "dodge") +
   facet_wrap(~ ca, scales = "free") +
   coord_flip() +
   tidyquant::theme_tq() +
   scale_fill_grey(start = 0.2, end = 0.5,
                   labels = c("Higher participation", "Lower participation")) +
   scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 120,  20), limits = c(0, 120)) +
   theme(#strip.background = element_rect(fill = "grey20"),
         strip.background = element_blank(),
         strip.text.x = element_text(size = 18, color = "grey20"),
         legend.title = element_blank(),
         legend.position = "bottom",
         legend.text = element_text(size = 16),
         text = element_text(size = 14, family = "Times New Roman")) +
   labs(x  = "Technical efficiency (%)\n",
        y = "\nFrequency")
